abstract: Data shows that so-called 'tech support rage,' frustration experienced by millions of customers as they contend with byzantine menus and unhelpful scripted responses, is intentionally engineered by companies; businesses often have limited amount of hands-on support to provide, and seek to deter increasingly savvy customers from consuming resources; experts say most egregious culprits are cable and mobile service providers.

abstract: Closing of gas station at corner of Lafayette and East Houston Streets leaves no operating gas stations in lower Manhattan; in previous eight years, 30 stations have closed in Manhattan, leaving only 50 in borough; shutdowns are symptom of hot real estate market, where property owners can make millions more for selling or developing than retail operations like gas stations can bring in.

abstract: Germana Soares and Glecion Amorim, young Brazilian couple who harbored middle-class dreams, have seen their fortunes dashed by country's economic instability and spread of Zika virus; Amorim lost job as welder during oil industry scandal-related downturn, and couple's child was born with Zika-related birth defects; their struggle exemplifies that of millions faced with raising disabled child while living in poverty.

abstract: Revival of checkpoints on some of Europe's most trafficked transit routes due to migration crisis is causing delays, impeding commerce and threatening to cost billions of euros in lost business, as continent continues to recover from six-year economic slump; critics worry that checkpoints spell permanent end to so-called Schengen Agreement, which allowed free movement of people and products between countries and helped turn European Union into economic powerhouse.

abstract: Nate Parker film The Birth of a Nation has received enormous critical response at Sundance Film Festival, sparking bidding war between studios that Fox Searchlight has won by offering unprecedented $17.5 million for distribution rights; response to film, which is slave-revolt historical drama that stars Parker and features diverse cast, comes even as Academy Awards is facing widespread criticism for its all-white field of acting nominees.
